Author: dusman05
Content: To anyone that‚Äôs going through their career or in corporate life, I‚Äôm currently at my very early stage, got a decent Marketing/Sales analyst role out of Uni. What advice would you give me in my position right now?

Author: dusman05
Content: what specific field of business would it be? it‚Äôs super broad. I think narrowing your focus and being specialized in a specific field is best.

Author: slickboizak
Content: im interested in management

Author: chrysal
Content: Learn data analysis (your SQL/python/powerBI/tableau), learn CRM

Author: dusman05
Content: Yes this is great advice! I‚Äôm pretty proficient with Excel and SQL. Python is on my mind to learn. atm in my company i‚Äôm using  Hubspot. Identified lots of key inefficiencies to streamline since day one and so far higher ups really liking the job i‚Äôve done.

Author: dusman05
Content: Gotcha. I would look at what career paths there are in Management post graduation, and maybe creating a roadmap in your mind for what key achievements you want to hit throughout university to ensure you are on the right track.

Author: chrysal
Content: Maybe the last advice would be - forecasting model

Author: dusman05
Content: we have automated most of this with the e commerce team in the company and I am not in charge of it so far, but would never hurt to learn more

Author: dusman05
Content: we have a major screw up in Q4 sales data as non b2b customers were being tagged as b2b so that‚Äôs on my task list to cleanup before year ends lol for accurate forecasting and analysis

Author: chrysal
Content: And learn basic finance - your ratios

Author: chrysal
Content: Cause it's always a pain point for finance team if you work on sales only mindset

Author: dusman05
Content: for sure. our margins are looking good this year

Author: dusman05
Content: Revenues are up 50%, Margins increased slightly

Author: chrysal
Content: Ideally you'd want to know what's their target margin for specific products

Author: dusman05
Content: overall on the right path to scaling up

Author: dusman05
Content: Our bestselling products are our key drivers, most of the ones that have been at our core since company‚Äôs founding. So far the ones that sre struggling are the newer products

Author: dusman05
Content: the core stuff constitues like 80% of our sales

Author: dusman05
Content: just because there‚Äôs more B2B appeal to it

Author: dusman05
Content: the newer products are more focused on D2C segments and have lower margins afaik cause we are trying to compete with different brands than who we compete with on our core offerings

Author: chrysal
Content: But overall i think you need no more advice :pray: you know your game better than most of us

Author: dusman05
Content: thanks man. it never hurts to learn more though

Author: aexion_forskin
Content: I've been considering to shift my focus from web development to cyber security, because I didn't think I had that much time building a projects (I always get distracted). What you guys think? (I'm at fourth semester taking a diploma on informatics, so yeah I only have 2 semester to learn it before TA)

Author: shiawase6946
Content:
Cyber Security is a whole different beast in itself dude. 

For web development, I think you can divide your project into chunks:
- Divide per module,
- Some module (esp the main functions) might be huge, so divide them again into features,
- Focus on Building, as long as it runs, and no error during compile. You can Test and Fix stuffs later when everything has been fully made.
- Use Sprint; divide into weekly Targets based on Modules/Features/Test case you need. 

Of course use AI to help. If you are freebies use more than one AI. Better if you can find AI that can run in IDE. Else just use Chat
